===Etymology===
From {{der|en|NL.|anarchia}}, from {{der|en|grc|ἀναρχία}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈæ.nə.ki/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|ănʹär-kē}}, {{IPA|/ˈæn.ɑɹ.ki/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~|anarchies}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable}} The state of a society being without [[authorities]] or an [[authoritative]] [[govern]]ing body.
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[anarchism|Anarchism]]; the political [[theory]] that a [[community]] is best [[organize|organized]] by the [[voluntary]] [[cooperation]] of [[individual]]s, rather than by a [[government]], which is regarded as being [[coercive]] by nature.
# {{lb|en|countable}} A [[chaotic]] and confusing [[absence]] of any form of [[political]] [[authority]] or [[government]].
# [[confusion|Confusion]] in general; [[disorder]].

====Usage notes====
* {{sense|confusion or misunderstanding in general}} Anarchists feel it is inappropriate to use ''anarchy'' to mean “a state of chaos or confusion”. However, this has historically been a common use of the word.

